---
import LocationLayout from '../../layouts/LocationLayout.astro';
import { marsLocations } from '../../data/marsLocations';

const location = marsLocations.find(loc => loc.id === 'arabia-terra');
if (!location) {
  throw new Error('Arabia Terra location not found');
}
---

<LocationLayout title="Arabia Terra - Mars Location" location={location}>
  <!-- Hero Image Section -->
  <div class="mb-8">
    <div
      class="relative h-96 bg-gradient-to-r from-red-900 to-orange-700 rounded-lg overflow-hidden"
    >
      <div class="absolute inset-0 bg-black/20"></div>
      <div class="absolute bottom-6 left-6 text-white">
        <p class="text-sm opacity-80">
          Ancient calderas in Arabia Terra revealing supervolcanic history
        </p>
        <p class="text-xs opacity-60">NASA/JPL-Caltech/ASU</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Overview Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">Overview</h2>
    <div class="grid lg:grid-cols-3 gap-8">
      <div class="lg:col-span-2">
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          Arabia Terra represents one of Mars' most ancient and geologically 
          significant highland regions, harboring evidence of massive supervolcanic 
          eruptions that fundamentally shaped the planet's early history. This 
          expansive terrain, covering thousands of square kilometers, preserves 
          a record of explosive volcanism that rivals Earth's most catastrophic 
          volcanic events.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          Recent discoveries have revealed that Arabia Terra experienced thousands 
          of "super eruptions" over a 500-million-year period approximately 4 
          billion years ago. These massive volcanic events expelled the equivalent 
          of 400 million Olympic-sized swimming pools of molten rock and gas, 
          creating calderas and fundamentally altering Mars' early climate and 
          geological evolution.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
          The region is characterized by abundant clay-bearing rocks, evidence 
          of ancient hydrothermal activity, and numerous calderas that were 
          previously misidentified as impact craters. This treasure trove of 
          geological diversity makes Arabia Terra a prime target for understanding 
          Mars' transition from a potentially habitable world to its current state.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Quick Facts Sidebar -->
      <div class="bg-gray-800/50 p-6 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">Quick Facts</h3>
        <div class="space-y-3">
          <div>
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">Age:</span>
            <span class="text-white block">4+ billion years (Noachian)</span>
          </div>
          <div>
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">Volcanic Period:</span>
            <span class="text-white block">500 million years active</span>
          </div>
          <div>
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">Calderas Identified:</span>
            <span class="text-white block">7+ supervolcano calderas</span>
          </div>
          <div>
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">Rock Type:</span>
            <span class="text-white block">Clay-bearing, altered minerals</span>
          </div>
          <div>
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">Significance:</span>
            <span class="text-white block">Ancient highland terrain</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Supervolcano Discovery Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">
      Supervolcano Calderas: A Geological Revolution
    </h2>
    <div class="bg-gray-800/30 p-8 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
      <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-6">
        What were once thought to be ancient impact craters have been revealed 
        as massive volcanic calderas formed by supervolcanic eruptions. These 
        calderas collapsed inward after explosive eruptions emptied underground 
        magma chambers, creating the distinctive basin-like features we observe today.
      </p>
      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
        <div>
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-3">Caldera Characteristics</h4>
          <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
            Seven major calderas have been identified, each representing collapsed 
            volcanic structures similar to terrestrial supervolcanoes like Yellowstone. 
            These low-relief features possess complex topographic depressions with 
            evidence of structural collapse, effusive volcanism, and explosive eruptions.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-3">Eruption Scale</h4>
          <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
            The scale of volcanic activity was enormous, with individual eruptions 
            capable of degassing approximately 100 million kilograms of sulfur 
            compounds into the atmosphere. These eruptions would have had profound 
            climate-altering effects on early Mars.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Ancient Volcanic Activity Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">
      500 Million Years of Explosive Volcanism
    </h2>

    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-1 gap-6 mb-8">
      <div
        class="bg-gradient-to-br from-red-900/50 to-orange-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-red-700/50"
      >
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">
          Thousands of Super Eruptions
        </h3>
        <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm mb-4">
          Arabia Terra experienced thousands of supervolcanic eruptions during 
          a 500-million-year period around 4 billion years ago. These eruptions 
          expelled massive volumes of water vapor, carbon dioxide, and sulfur 
          dioxide into the atmosphere, fundamentally altering Mars' early climate.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
          Each super eruption was capable of blasting hundreds of millions of 
          tons of molten rock and gas through the surface, spreading thick 
          blankets of ash across thousands of miles and leaving behind massive 
          calderas when the volcanic structures collapsed.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-gray-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
      <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">
        Climate and Atmospheric Impact
      </h3>
      <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">
        The massive scale of volcanic outgassing from Arabia Terra's supervolcanoes 
        would have dramatically altered Mars' early atmosphere and climate. The 
        eruptions injected enormous quantities of sulfur compounds, water vapor, 
        and other gases that could have supported a thicker atmosphere and 
        potentially warmer surface conditions.
      </p>
      <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
        However, these same eruptions may have also contributed to atmospheric 
        loss over time, as the massive dust clouds and chemical changes could 
        have triggered cooling events and atmospheric escape processes that 
        gradually transformed Mars into the cold, dry world we see today.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Geological Evidence Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">
      Preserved Volcanic Evidence
    </h2>
    <div class="grid lg:grid-cols-3 gap-6">
      <div class="lg:col-span-2">
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          The geological evidence for Arabia Terra's supervolcanic past is 
          remarkably well preserved in the mineral composition and layered 
          deposits throughout the region. Recent analysis has revealed that 
          the volcanic ash layers remain intact and clearly stratified, 
          providing a detailed record of individual eruption events.
        </p>

        <div class="space-y-4 mb-6">
          <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
            <h4 class="font-semibold text-white mb-2">
              Mineral Evidence
            </h4>
            <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
              Clay-bearing rocks throughout Arabia Terra show evidence of 
              hydrothermal alteration from volcanic processes and water interaction.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="border-l-4 border-orange-500 pl-4">
            <h4 class="font-semibold text-white mb-2">
              Ash Layer Preservation
            </h4>
            <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
              Well-preserved ash layers show clear stratification without wind 
              or water mixing, indicating rapid deposition and burial.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="border-l-4 border-yellow-500 pl-4">
            <h4 class="font-semibold text-white mb-2">
              Pyroclastic Deposits
            </h4>
            <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
              Low-density pyroclastic deposits detected through gravitational 
              modeling support explosive volcanic origin theories.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-gray-800/50 p-6 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">
          Research Techniques
        </h3>
        <div class="space-y-3">
          <div class="flex justify-between">
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">Mineral Mapping:</span>
            <span class="text-white text-sm">Orbital spectrometry</span>
          </div>
          <div class="flex justify-between">
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">Topography:</span>
            <span class="text-white text-sm">MOLA altimetry</span>
          </div>
          <div class="flex justify-between">
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">Gravity:</span>
            <span class="text-white text-sm">Modeling analysis</span>
          </div>
          <div class="flex justify-between">
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">Dating:</span>
            <span class="text-white text-sm">Crater counting</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Habitability Implications Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">
      Early Mars Habitability Implications
    </h2>
    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mb-8">
      <div
        class="bg-gradient-to-br from-green-900/50 to-blue-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-green-700/50"
      >
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">
          Hydrothermal Systems
        </h3>
        <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm mb-4">
          The massive volcanic activity in Arabia Terra would have created 
          extensive hydrothermal systems - environments where heated water 
          interacts with rock, potentially creating conditions suitable for 
          early life. The clay-bearing rocks throughout the region provide 
          evidence of these water-rock interactions.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
          Hydrothermal environments are considered some of the most promising 
          locations for early life on Earth, and similar conditions in Arabia 
          Terra may have provided habitable niches during Mars' early history.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div
        class="bg-gradient-to-br from-purple-900/50 to-indigo-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-purple-700/50"
      >
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">
          Atmospheric Evolution
        </h3>
        <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm mb-4">
          The supervolcanic eruptions contributed to Mars' atmospheric evolution 
          by releasing massive amounts of gases. While initially thickening the 
          atmosphere and potentially warming the surface, the long-term effects 
          may have contributed to atmospheric loss processes.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
          Understanding this volcanic influence is crucial for modeling Mars' 
          transition from potentially habitable conditions to its current state.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Terraforming Assessment Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">
      Terraforming Assessment
    </h2>
    <div
      class="bg-gradient-to-br from-yellow-900/30 to-orange-800/20 p-8 rounded-lg border border-yellow-700/50"
    >
      <div class="flex items-center mb-6">
        <div
          class="w-12 h-12 bg-orange-600 rounded-full flex items-center justify-center mr-4"
        >
          <span class="text-white font-bold text-xl">7</span>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-white">
            Good Terraforming Potential
          </h3>
          <p class="text-orange-300">
            Rich mineral resources and geological diversity
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
        <div>
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-3">Advantages</h4>
          <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-300 text-sm">
            <li>• Abundant clay-bearing rocks for construction</li>
            <li>• Evidence of past hydrothermal systems</li>
            <li>• Diverse mineral resources from volcanic activity</li>
            <li>• Ancient highland elevation advantages</li>
            <li>• Rich geological record for resource mapping</li>
            <li>• Potential geothermal energy sources</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-3">Challenges</h4>
          <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-300 text-sm">
            <li>• Limited current water resources</li>
            <li>• Dust accumulation in highland terrain</li>
            <li>• Ancient surface with impact crater hazards</li>
            <li>• Radiation exposure concerns</li>
            <li>• Temperature variations at elevation</li>
            <li>• Complex terrain navigation</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Scientific Significance Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">
      Scientific Significance
    </h2>
    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-gray-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">
          Planetary Evolution Archive
        </h3>
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
          Arabia Terra serves as a natural laboratory for understanding how 
          massive volcanism can shape planetary evolution. The preserved record 
          of 500 million years of supervolcanic activity provides unprecedented 
          insights into early Mars' geological processes and their role in 
          atmospheric and climate evolution.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-gray-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">
          Comparative Planetology
        </h3>
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
          The scale of volcanic activity preserved in Arabia Terra exceeds 
          anything seen on Earth, making it crucial for understanding how 
          extreme volcanism affects planetary habitability. This research 
          informs our understanding of volcanic processes on other worlds and 
          the role of volcanism in planetary evolution throughout the solar system.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Future Exploration Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">
      Future Exploration Opportunities
    </h2>
    <div
      class="bg-gradient-to-br from-purple-900/30 to-purple-800/20 p-8 rounded-lg border border-purple-700/50"
    >
      <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-6">
        Arabia Terra represents a high-priority target for future Mars exploration 
        due to its unique geological history and potential for understanding 
        early Martian habitability. The region's diverse mineral assemblages 
        and well-preserved volcanic record make it ideal for both robotic and 
        eventually human exploration.
      </p>

      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
        <div>
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-3">
            Priority Research Goals
          </h4>
          <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-300 text-sm">
            <li>• Detailed caldera floor exploration</li>
            <li>• Hydrothermal deposit analysis</li>
            <li>• Ancient volcanic ash sampling</li>
            <li>• Clay mineral characterization</li>
            <li>• Astrobiology investigations</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-3">
            Resource Potential
          </h4>
          <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-300 text-sm">
            <li>• Clay minerals for construction materials</li>
            <li>• Volcanic glass for manufacturing</li>
            <li>• Hydrothermal mineral deposits</li>
            <li>• Potential geothermal energy sites</li>
            <li>• Water-altered rock resources</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- External Resources Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">Learn More</h2>
    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
      <div class="bg-gray-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-4">Scientific Papers</h3>
        <ul class="space-y-2">
          <li>
            <a
              href="https://www.nature.com/articles/nature12482"
              class="text-blue-400 hover:text-blue-300 text-sm"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noopener noreferrer"
            >
              Supervolcanoes in Arabia Terra (Nature)
            </a>
          </li>
          <li>
            <a
              href="https://agupubs.onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/full/10.1029/2021GL093118"
              class="text-blue-400 hover:text-blue-300 text-sm"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noopener noreferrer"
            >
              Caldera Collapse and Volcanic Resurfacing (2021)
            </a>
          </li>
          <li>
            <a
              href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0019103522003955"
              class="text-blue-400 hover:text-blue-300 text-sm"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noopener noreferrer"
            >
              Supervolcanic Resurfacing Evidence
            </a>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-gray-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-4">NASA Resources</h3>
        <ul class="space-y-2">
          <li>
            <a
              href="https://www.nasa.gov/solar-system/nasa-confirms-thousands-of-massive-ancient-volcanic-eruptions-on-mars/"
              class="text-blue-400 hover:text-blue-300 text-sm"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noopener noreferrer"
            >
              NASA Supervolcano Discovery News
            </a>
          </li>
          <li>
            <a
              href="https://mars.nasa.gov/news/9039/nasa-confirms-thousands-of-massive-ancient-volcanic-eruptions-on-mars/"
              class="text-blue-400 hover:text-blue-300 text-sm"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noopener noreferrer"
            >
              Mars Exploration Program Coverage
            </a>
          </li>
          <li>
            <a
              href="https://www.planetary.org/space-images/calderas-in-arabia-terra"
              class="text-blue-400 hover:text-blue-300 text-sm"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noopener noreferrer"
            >
              Calderas in Arabia Terra - Planetary Society
            </a>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</LocationLayout>